1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:04,850
In this video we are going to learn RabbitMQ exchange types.

2
00:00:04,880 --> 00:00:09,590
Here you can see the exchange sitting between producer and queues.

3
00:00:10,220 --> 00:00:13,880
Exchange control the routing of the messages to queues.

4
00:00:14,090 --> 00:00:21,290
Each exchange type defines a specific routing algorithm, which the server uses to determine that bound

5
00:00:21,290 --> 00:00:23,930
queues a published message should be routed to.

6
00:00:24,620 --> 00:00:27,980
So RabbitMQ provides four types of the exchange.

7
00:00:28,010 --> 00:00:32,360
These are the direct fan out topic and headers.

8
00:00:32,390 --> 00:00:35,360
So let me start with the direct exchange.

9
00:00:35,720 --> 00:00:40,820
Indirect exchange uses of a single queue is being addressed.

10
00:00:41,150 --> 00:00:47,480
A routing key is determined according to the things to be done, and accordingly the most appropriate

11
00:00:47,480 --> 00:00:54,830
queue is reached with the relevant direct exchange, and the next exchange type is a topic exchange.

12
00:00:54,830 --> 00:01:00,860
In topic exchange, messages are sent to different queues according to their subject.

13
00:01:00,860 --> 00:01:08,000
The incoming message is classified and sent to the related queue, and a route is used to send the message

14
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:09,740
to one or more queues.

15
00:01:10,220 --> 00:01:13,490
It is a variation of the publish subscriber pattern.

16
00:01:13,490 --> 00:01:20,330
If the problem concerns several consumers, topic exchange should be used to determine what kind of

17
00:01:20,330 --> 00:01:22,010
message they want to receive.

18
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:26,140
So the next exchange type is Fanout exchange.

19
00:01:26,170 --> 00:01:31,570
It is used in situations where the message should be sent to more than one queue.

20
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:34,960
It is especially applied in broadcasting systems.

21
00:01:34,990 --> 00:01:43,060
It is mainly used for the games for global announcements, and the last exchange type is header exchange.

22
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:50,710
In headers exchange, you guided by the features added to the header of the message routing key used

23
00:01:50,710 --> 00:01:52,870
in other modules is not used.

24
00:01:52,900 --> 00:01:58,120
Transmits to the correct queue with a few features and descriptions in a message.

25
00:01:58,120 --> 00:01:58,780
Headers.

26
00:01:58,780 --> 00:02:04,540
The attributes of the header and the attributes on the queue must match each other's values.

